# Corporate Advisory Analyst

## Overview
An entry-level role in boutique advisory or investment banking divisions, supporting M&A, capital markets, and debt advisory transactions through financial modeling, valuation analysis, and deal execution for clients ranging from mid-market to large corporates.

## Core Responsibilities
- Build detailed three-statement financial models, DCF valuations, comparable company analyses, and transaction models while conducting industry research and market analysis under tight deadlines.
- Create PowerPoint pitch books, information memoranda, management presentations, and board materials, incorporating multiple rounds of feedback to meet exacting professional standards.
- Manage transaction processes including virtual data rooms, due diligence coordination, bid process administration, and preparation of transaction timelines and comparison matrices.
- Support regulatory compliance by assisting with ASIC filings, ASX announcements, takeover documentation, and FIRB submissions while coordinating with legal counsel on disclosure requirements.
- Conduct target identification and market screening for buy-side mandates, build potential buyer lists for sell-side processes, and maintain market intelligence on competitor transactions.
- Work across multiple live transactions simultaneously, prioritizing urgent requests, managing competing deadlines, and maintaining accuracy and quality under extreme time pressure throughout execution.

## Key Skills Required

### Technical Skills
- Expert Excel proficiency including three-statement modeling, DCF/LBO valuation, and formula auditing
- Strong understanding of AASB/IFRS accounting principles and financial statement analysis
- Advanced PowerPoint skills for data visualization and professional presentation design
- Knowledge of Australian M&A market dynamics, recent transactions, and valuation trends

### Regulatory Knowledge
- Understanding of Corporations Act takeover provisions and scheme of arrangement mechanics
- Familiarity with ASIC continuous disclosure, ASX Listing Rules, and shareholder approval thresholds
- Knowledge of FIRB foreign investment screening and ACCC merger clearance processes
- Awareness of prospectus requirements, insider trading laws, and corporate governance standards

### Professional Skills
- Ability to work 60-80+ hour weeks while maintaining quality under intense time pressure
- Zero-tolerance attention to detail for catching errors in client-facing materials
- Strong teamwork skills and ability to take constructive feedback during high-pressure situations
- Clear written and verbal communication for explaining complex financial concepts
- Commercial judgment to understand client motivations and anticipate senior banker needs
- Effective time management across multiple deals and ability to escalate issues appropriately

## Work Mode

### Analytical Work (50-60%)
Building and updating valuation models, merger models, and transaction analyses; analyzing financial statements and calculating metrics; conducting industry research and company analysis; reviewing colleagues' models for errors.

### Document Production (30-35%)
Creating PowerPoint pitch books, board presentations, and transaction updates; drafting information memoranda with company descriptions and market analysis; formatting materials to professional standards; detailed proofreading of client documents.

### Process Management (5-10%)
Coordinating email flows between clients, lawyers, accountants, and buyers; managing data room document uploads and Q&A tracking; updating transaction timelines and flagging critical issues; preparing meeting agendas and follow-up actions.

### Client Meetings (5-10%)
Attending internal team meetings and deal catch-ups; participating in client meetings primarily for listening and note-taking in first year; attending technical training and presentation skills development; building relationships with senior bankers.

### After-Hours Work (Variable)
Responding to urgent requests and deadline changes outside standard hours; weekend work common during busy deal periods and pitch deadlines; checking emails most weekends; expect full weekend work when transactions approach signing or closings.

## Workplace Culture
High-intensity, high-stakes environment with steep hierarchy and demanding hours; "up or out" performance culture with low error tolerance; strong learning through deal exposure and mentorship; unpredictable schedules requiring flexibility.

## Career Path
- Entry: Analyst (0-2 years post-university, \$120k-\$180k total comp)
- Progression: Senior Analyst/Associate (2-3 years) → Associate (\$250k-\$400k+) → VP (5-7 years, \$350k-\$600k+) → Director → Managing Director (10+ years, \$300k-\$1m+); common pivots to private equity, corporate development, consulting, or venture capital after 2-3 years

